{"title_page": "Net Park", "text_new": "'''Seven/NEO (formerly Net Park)''' is a 48-story green and sustainable corporate tower located in [[Bonifacio Global City]], [[Metro Manila]], [[Philippines]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Net Park|url=http://kmcmaggroup.com/building/Net-Park/|website=kmcmaggroup.com|publisher=KMC MAG Group}}</ref> It is part of the office space portfolio of NEO (formerly TNG), a developer who pioneered the concept of IT office building in the Philippines. The building is one out of two of NEO's sustainable building [[mixed-use development]]and is considered as the nation\u2019s first certified green project in Taguig.\n\nThe property was developed by Charlie Rufino of the [[Rufino Family]] and designed by [[Oppenheim Architecture + Design|Chad Oppenheim]], a Miami-based architect who specializes in green architecture. It will be built with the second Ascott Residences in the Philippines and was expected to reach completion in 2015,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cu-Unjieng|first1=Philip|title=Building Green|url=http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/features/properties/15504-the-net-group-wins-international-property-awards|accessdate=June 19, 2014|publisher=Philippine Star|date=Sep 4, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104051738/http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/features/properties/15504-the-net-group-wins-international-property-awards|archivedate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> but was completed in 2016.<ref>https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1208252/net-park-taguig-philippines Emporis, Net Park</ref> Net Park is home to the Google head office in The Philippines.\n\n\n==Features==\nSeven/NEO has over 62,000 sqm. of office space with an estimated height of 38 floors.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morales|first1=Neil Jerome C.|title=Net Group hikes office space portfolio|url=http://www.philstar.com/business/2013/04/08/928086/net-group-hikes-office-space-portfolio|accessdate=June 19, 2014|publisher=The Philippine Star|date=April 8, 2013}}</ref> It will have grade A office floor plates with a full retail ground level, podium, and park. Net Park is slated to receive a BERDE certification. BERDE or more formally known as Building for Ecologically Responsive Design Excellence Program  is a green building rating system created by the [[Philippine Green Building Council]] to measure, verify, and monitor performance of buildings in the Philippines.\n\n==Design==\nThe skyscraper has passive external shading devices, roof mounted vertical access wind turbines, and a graywater reuse system designed to irrigate all on site landscaping. The towers are orientated to rotate of the other axis to allow natural light into the building and harness maximum sunlight penetration. Interior columns are also minimized to provide floor efficiency and every floor plate is flexible to accommodate differing tenant demands.<ref>{{cite web|title=NET METROPOLIS|url=http://www.oppenoffice.com/index.php?test=test&option=com_k2&view=item&id=156:net-metropolis&Itemid=53#.U6J8KvmSzw9|website=oppenoffice.com/|publisher=Oppenheim Architecture+Design|accessdate=June 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nSeven/NEO is built along 5th Ave., one of the main thoroughfares in [[Fort Bonifacio]] (Bonifacio Global City). It is on the same street as the [[Sun Life]] Centre, another green building certified by [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] and within the same block of major entertainment and dining complexes in BGC: Bonifacio High Street and The Fort Strip.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Metro Manila]]\n\n{{Bonifacio Global City}}\n{{Manila Skyscrapers}}\n\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Bonifacio Global City]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Metro Manila]]\n", "text_old": "'''Net Park''' is a 48-story green and sustainable corporate tower located in [[Bonifacio Global City]], [[Metro Manila]], [[Philippines]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Net Park|url=http://kmcmaggroup.com/building/Net-Park/|website=kmcmaggroup.com|publisher=KMC MAG Group}}</ref> It is part of the office space portfolio of the Net Group, a developer who pioneered the concept of IT office building in the Philippines. The building will be part of the Net Metropolis 5th Ave, a [[mixed-use development]] considered as the nation\u2019s first certified green project in Taguig.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Miraflor|first1=Madelaine|title=Net Group to build P1-billion tower next year|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/net-group-to-build-p1-billion-tower-next-year/44450/|accessdate=June 19, 2014|publisher=The Manila Times|date=Oct 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Net Park is the second tower to rise in the Net Metropolis, 5th Avenue. The property was developed by Charlie Rufino of the [[Rufino Family]] and designed by [[Oppenheim Architecture + Design|Chad Oppenheim]], a Miami-based architect who specializes in green architecture. It will be built with the second Ascott Residences in the Philippines and was expected to reach completion in 2015,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cu-Unjieng|first1=Philip|title=Building Green|url=http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/features/properties/15504-the-net-group-wins-international-property-awards|accessdate=June 19, 2014|publisher=Philippine Star|date=Sep 4, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104051738/http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/features/properties/15504-the-net-group-wins-international-property-awards|archivedate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> but was completed in 2016.<ref>https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1208252/net-park-taguig-philippines Emporis, Net Park</ref> Net Park is home to the Google head office in The Philippines.\n\n\n==Features==\nThe Net Park has over 62,000 sqm. of office space with an estimated height of 38 floors.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morales|first1=Neil Jerome C.|title=Net Group hikes office space portfolio|url=http://www.philstar.com/business/2013/04/08/928086/net-group-hikes-office-space-portfolio|accessdate=June 19, 2014|publisher=The Philippine Star|date=April 8, 2013}}</ref> It will have grade A office floor plates with a full retail ground level, podium, and park. Net Park is slated to receive a BERDE certification. BERDE or more formally known as Building for Ecologically Responsive Design Excellence Program  is a green building rating system created by the [[Philippine Green Building Council]] to measure, verify, and monitor performance of buildings in the Philippines.\n\n==Design==\nTogether with the other buildings in the Net Metropolis, Net Park is designed for [[sustainability]]. The skyscraper has passive external shading devices, roof mounted vertical access wind turbines, and a graywater reuse system designed to irrigate all on site landscaping. The towers are orientated to rotate of the other axis to allow natural light into the building and harness maximum sunlight penetration. Interior columns are also minimized to provide floor efficiency and every floor plate is flexible to accommodate differing tenant demands.<ref>{{cite web|title=NET METROPOLIS|url=http://www.oppenoffice.com/index.php?test=test&option=com_k2&view=item&id=156:net-metropolis&Itemid=53#.U6J8KvmSzw9|website=oppenoffice.com/|publisher=Oppenheim Architecture+Design|accessdate=June 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nThe Net Park is built along 5th Ave., one of the main thoroughfares in [[Fort Bonifacio]] (Bonifacio Global City). It is on the same street as the [[Sun Life]] Centre, another green building certified by [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] and within the same block of major entertainment and dining complexes in BGC: Bonifacio High Street and The Fort Strip.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Metro Manila]]\n\n{{Bonifacio Global City}}\n{{Manila Skyscrapers}}\n\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Bonifacio Global City]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Metro Manila]]\n", "name_user": "112.207.101.146", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Net_Park"}
{"title_page": "Sir Charles Farnaby-Radcliffe, 3rd Baronet", "text_new": "'''Sir Charles Farnaby-Radcliffe, 3rd Baronet'''   (c. 1740\u20131798) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] for 33 years between 1765 and 1798.  .\n\n[[File:Hitchin Priory (geograph 3566891).jpg|thumb|Hitchin Priory, now an hotel]]\nFarnaby was the eldest son of Sir Thomas Farnaby, 2nd Baronet and his wife Mary Lloyd, daughter of Rev. Montagu Lloyd. He was probably educated at [[Eton College]] from 1747 to 1754.  He succeeded his father in the [[Farnaby baronets|baronetcy]] on 24 March 1760. He married Penelope Charlton, widow of Richard Charlton,  a London merchant, and daughter of John Radcliffe of Hitchin Priory, Hertfordshire on 12 August 1762. When his brother-in-law [[John Radcliffe (1738-1783)|John Radcliffe]] died in 1783 his wife succeeded to his property including Hitchin Priory and Farnaby assumed the additional  name of Radcliffe 1784.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/farnaby-%28afterwards-farnaby-radcliffe%29-sir-charles-1740-98 | title= FARNABY (afterwards FARNABY RADCLIFFE), Sir Charles, 3rd Bt. (?1740-98), of Kippington, nr. Sevenoaks, Kent.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1754-1790)| accessdate = 1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nFarnaby was returned as  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[East Grinstead (UK Parliament constituency)|East Grinstead]] on the interest of [[George Germain, 1st Viscount Sackville|Lord George Sackville]] at a by-election on 30 December 1765. At the [[1768 British general election|1768 general election]] he and Sackville were both defeated at [[Hythe (UK Parliament constituency)|Hythe]].  Farnaby was returned unopposed for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]]  at a by-election on 15 February 1769.   He was then returned for Hythe with ministerial support at the [[1774 British general election|1774 general election]]   and again in [[1780 British general election|1780]]    and [[1784 British general election|1784]]  topping the poll each time.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nFarnaby-Ratcliffe's estates in  Kent gave him a powerful influence and he was returned without a contest for Hythe in [[1790 British general election|1790]] and [[1796 British general election|1796]]. He is not known to have spoken in Parliament during his time there.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/farnaby-radcliffe-sir-charles-1738-98 | title=FARNABY RADCLIFFE, Sir Charles, 3rd Bt. (?1738-98), of Kippington, near Sevenoaks, Kent and Hitchin Priory, Herts. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1790-1820)| accessdate = 1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nFarnaby died of a lingering illness in  October 1798 and was buried at Hitchin on the 20 October.<ref name = HOP2/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Charles Sackville, 2nd Duke of Dorset|The Earl of Middlesex]]\n | before2 = [[John Irwin (MP)|John Irwin]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[East Grinstead (UK Parliament constituency)|East Grinstead]]\n | years = 1765\u2013[[1768 British general election|1768]]\n | with  =  [[John Irwin (MP)|John Irwin]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[George Germain, 1st Viscount Sackville|Lord George Sackville]]\n | after2 = [[John Irwin (MP)|John Irwin]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Brook Bridges, 3rd Baronet|Sir Brook Bridges]]\n | before2 = [[John Sackville, 3rd Duke of Dorset|John Frederick Sackville]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]]\n | years = 1769\u2013[[1774 British general election|1774]]\n | with  =  [[Sir Brook Bridges, 3rd Baronet|Sir Brook Bridges]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Charles Marsham, 1st Earl of Romney|Hon. Charles Marsham]]\n | after2 = [[Thomas Knight (MP for Kent)|Thomas Knight, junior]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  =  [[John Sawbridge]]\n | before2 = [[William Evelyn (died 1813)|William Evelyn]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hythe (UK Parliament constituency)|Hythe]]\n | years = [[1774 British general election|1774]]\u20131798 \n | with  =  [[William Evelyn (died 1813)|William Evelyn]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Charles Marsham, 2nd Earl of Romney|Hon. Charles Marsham]]\n | after2 = [[William Evelyn (died 1813)|William Evelyn]]\n}}\n{{S-reg|en-bt}}\n{{S-bef| before= Sir Thomas Farnaby, 2nd Baronet }}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Farnaby baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of  Keppington) | years=1760-1798''' }}\n{{s-aft | after =  Sir John Farnaby, 4th Baronet   }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farnaby-Radcliffe, Sir Charles,  3rd Baronet}}\n[[Category:1740s births]]\n[[Category:1798 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1761\u20131768]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1768\u20131774]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1790\u20131796]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir Charles Farnaby-Radcliffe, 3rd Baronet'''   (c. 1740\u20131798) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] for 33 years between 1765 and 1798.  .\n\n[[File:Hitchin Priory (geograph 3566891).jpg|thumb|Hitchin Priory, now an hotel]]\nFarnaby was the eldest son of Sir Thomas Farnaby, 2nd Baronet and his wife Mary Lloyd, daughter of Rev. Montagu Lloyd. He was probably educated at [[Eton College]] from 1747 to 1754.  He succeeded his father in the [[Farnaby baronets|baronetcy]] on 24 March 1760. He married Penelope Charlton, widow of Richard Charlton,  a London merchant, and daughter of John Radcliffe of Hitchin Priory, Hertfordshire on 12 August 1762. When his brother-in-law [[John Radcliffe (1738-1783)|John Radcliffe]] died in 1783 his wife succeeded to his property including Hitchin Priory and Farnaby assumed the additional  name of Radcliffe 1784.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/farnaby-%28afterwards-farnaby-radcliffe%29-sir-charles-1740-98 | title= FARNABY (afterwards FARNABY RADCLIFFE), Sir Charles, 3rd Bt. (?1740-98), of Kippington, nr. Sevenoaks, Kent.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1754-1790)| accessdate = 1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nFarnaby was returned as  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[East Grinstead (UK Parliament constituency)|East Grinstead]] on the interest of [[George Germain, 1st Viscount Sackville|Lord George Sackville]] at a by-election on 30 December 1765. At the [[1768 British general election|1768 general election]] he and Sackville were both defeated at [[Hythe (UK Parliament constituency)|Hythe]].  Farnaby was returned unopposed for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]]  at a by-election on 15 February 1769.   He was then returned for Hythe with ministerial support at the [[1774 British general election|1774 general election]]   and again in [[1780 British general election|1780]]    and [[1784 British general election|1784]]  topping the poll each time.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nFarnaby-Ratcliffe\u2019s estates in  Kent gave him a powerful influence and he was returned without a contest for Hythe in [[1790 British general election|1790]] and [[1796 British general election|1796]]. He is not known to have spoken in Parliament during his time there.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/farnaby-radcliffe-sir-charles-1738-98 | title=FARNABY RADCLIFFE, Sir Charles, 3rd Bt. (?1738-98), of Kippington, near Sevenoaks, Kent and Hitchin Priory, Herts. | publisher= History of Parliament Online (1790-1820)| accessdate = 1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nFarnaby died of a lingering illness in  October 1798 and was buried at Hitchin on the 20 October.<ref name = HOP2/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{